            <p>Washington&#44; D. C.<lb/>
                September&#44; 11&#44; 1882.<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev. and dear friend.<lb/></p>
            <p>As my old<lb/> friends drop off&#58; Those who<lb/> were firm in the faith&#44; and<lb/> whose &#34;Orthodoxy&#34; was their<lb/> cardinal principle&#44; I am<lb/> lead to set even greater<lb/> store upon those who are<lb/> left&#44; and among these few<lb/>&#45;&#45;these very few&#8212;yourself<lb/> is the most <sic>conspicuos</sic><lb/> among public men&#44; and<lb/> therefore&#44; aside from your<lb/> being my &#34;friend&#34;&#45;&#45;a name<lb/> I apply in this connection<lb/> to but very few&#8212;it is both<lb/> a pleasure and a duty<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>to wish you at this holy<lb/> season a very&#44; <hi rend="underline">very</hi> Happy<lb/> New Year&#44;&#34; coupled with<lb/> the sincere prayer that<lb/> your valuable life may<lb/> be spared to your esteem&#45;<lb/>ed family and the world<lb/> for many years to come<lb/> and that during all<lb/> these years health and<lb/> unalloyed happiness may<lb/> be yours.<lb/></p>
            <p>I need <sic>scarsely</sic> add<lb/> that I trust the same<lb/> form of Divine Providence<lb/> may extend to every mem&#45;<lb/>ber of your family&#44; to whom<lb/> my regards&#44; in which my<lb/> household desire to unite&#44;<lb/> and believe me&#44; honored Sir&#44;<lb/></p>
            <p>Yours Sincerely<lb/>
                A. S. Solomons<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev. S. Morais.<lb/></p>
        </body>
    </text>
